Background

This week, you are to become familiar with Kaggle.com and use the House Prices Advanced Regression Techniques(https://www.kaggle.com/c/house-prices-advanced-regression-techniques) to an external site. Kaggle competition to hone your Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA) skills. The dependent variable of interest is house prices in Ames, Iowa (SalePrice).

Management/Research Question

In laymans terms, what is the management/research question of interest, and why would anyone care?

Requirements

You are to conduct EDA on the dataset as follows.

Provide appropriate descriptive statistics and visualizations to help understand the marginal distribution of the dependent variable. Investigate missing data and outliers. Investigate at least three potential predictors of the dependent variable and provide appropriate graphs / statistics to demonstrate the relationships. Engage in feature creation by splitting, merging, or otherwise generating a new predictor.

Using the dependent variable, perform both min-max and standard scaling in Python. (Some methods we will learn in this course (trees and random forests) are unaffected by monotonic transformations of the explanatory variables. Others (SVMs and neural networks) are very much affected by scaling and usually perform better when all explanatory variables have the same scale. It is often best to use scaling methods that preserve the shape of the distribution. But if there are extreme outliers or heavily skewed distributions, then log or normalizing transformations may be warranted.)

# Engage in feature creation by splitting, merging, or otherwise generating a new predictor.

# Create a new feature called 'TotalSF' by adding the square footage of all floors and the basement together
train["TotalSF"] = train["1stFlrSF"] + train["2ndFlrSF"] + train["TotalBsmtSF"]


# Create a new feature called 'TotalBath' by adding the number of full bathrooms and half bathrooms together
train["TotalBath"] = train["FullBath"] + train["HalfBath"]


# Create a new feature called 'TotalPorchSF' by adding the square footage of all porches together
train["TotalPorchSF"] = (
    train["OpenPorchSF"]
    + train["EnclosedPorch"]
    + train["3SsnPorch"]
    + train["ScreenPorch"]
)

# Create a new feature called 'TotalOutsideSF' by adding the square footage of all porches together
train["TotalOutsideSF"] = (
    train["WoodDeckSF"]
    + train["OpenPorchSF"]
    + train["EnclosedPorch"]
    + train["3SsnPorch"]
    + train["ScreenPorch"]
)

# drop the old features
train.drop(
    [
        "1stFlrSF",
        "2ndFlrSF",
        "TotalBsmtSF",
        "FullBath",
        "HalfBath",
        "OpenPorchSF",
        "EnclosedPorch",
        "3SsnPorch",
        "ScreenPorch",
        "WoodDeckSF",
    ],
    axis=1,
    inplace=True,
)

train dataframe has 1460 rows, 81 columns. It is safe to assume that columns having more than 584 missing values (40% of the length) are not useful for our analysis. Columns to be excluded are as follows:

  • PoolQC : Pool quality
  • Alley : Type of alley access
  • Fence : Fence quality
  • MasVnrType : Masonry veneer type
  • FireplaceQu : Fireplace quality

LotFrontage also has significant number of missing values, however, we will impute the missing values with the mean of the column.

In [215]:
def should_drop(series):

    # Very low variance
    if series.var() < 0.01:
        return True
    # Top value accounts for more than 90%
    if series.value_counts(normalize=True).iloc[0] > 0.9:
        return True

    return False


to_drop = []
for col in train.columns:
    if train[col].dtype == 'object':
        continue
    if should_drop(train[col]):
        to_drop.append(col)

train.drop(to_drop, axis=1, inplace=True)
print(f"Dropped {len(to_drop)} columns with bad distributions.")
for col in to_drop:
    print(col)

import pandas as pd

# Subset to just numeric columns
numeric_cols = train.select_dtypes(include=["int", "float"])


# Function to detect outliers
def detect_outliers(series):
    cutoff = 3
    lower, upper = (
        series.mean() - cutoff * series.std(),
        series.mean() + cutoff * series.std(),
    )
    outliers = series[(series < lower) | (series > upper)]
    return outliers


# Identify outliers for each numeric column
outliers = {}
for col in numeric_cols:
    outliers[col] = detect_outliers(numeric_cols[col])

# Wrap in dictionary to dataframe
outliers = pd.DataFrame(outliers)

print(f"Identified {outliers.shape[0]} numeric outliers")

# collect indices
outlier_indices = []
for col in numeric_cols:
    outlier_indices.extend(outliers[col].index)


# Drop outliers
train = train.drop(outlier_indices)

print(f"{len(train)} rows remaining")

Identified 231 numeric outliers
1229 rows remaining

    train[col] = le.fit_transform(train[col].astype(str))
